<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="37.[264,1323,791,1097]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
COMMENTS. In 
<collectingCountry box="[529,607,871,897]" name="Belize" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Belize</collectingCountry>
, the highly cryptic, non­waxy, puparia of this species occur sparsely under the leaves of its aroid hosts, and are difficult to find. However, in areas of new introduction larger populations are normal until brought under control. This species seems likely to extend its range still further, resulting from the popular trade in ornamental aroids (such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Adanson" authorityYear="1763" box="[464,577,1031,1056]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Monstera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[464,577,1031,1056]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Monstera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[646,806,1031,1056]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Philodendron" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[646,806,1031,1056]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Philodendron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the 
<taxonomicName box="[886,982,1031,1057]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Araceae</taxonomicName>
being its only known host family at present.
</paragraph>
